         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1452">
               <p>Moore, a native of <placeName>Ireland</placeName>, was apprenticed to a wood
                  engraver. He was converted in <date when="1777-02">Feb. 1777</date> under the
                  influence of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0237.xml"/>Samuel
                     Bradburn</persName>, became a local preacher, and opened a school. He entered
                  the <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg> ministry in <date when="1779"
                     >1779</date> (see <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>, 10:484), serving first in
                     <placeName>Ireland</placeName> and then <placeName>England</placeName>. In
                     <date when="1780">1780</date> Young married <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1449.xml"/>Anne Young</persName> (<date from="1757"
                     to="1813">1757–1813</date>) of <placeName>Coleraine</placeName>. He resisted
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>&apos;s
                  suggestion of ordination in the Church of <placeName>England</placeName>, but was
                  one of three preachers ordained by <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> for the work in <placeName>England</placeName> in <date
                     when="1789">1789</date>. He is buried at <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>Wesley</persName>&apos;s Chapel in
                     <placeName>London</placeName>. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 788; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 244.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
